Can you please give an example on how to use hivethriftserver2 with kerberos / http transport mode.

I placed the following in extras and it is not working

{ "use_beeline": true, "principal": "hive/_HOST@XX.ADDS", "transportMode": "http", "httpPath: "cliservice", "proxy_user": "login"}

@yrqls21 @jgao54 correct, there might not be easy way to make the workers work in parallel with FAB initialization, as the gunicorn workers are actually independent unix process _(not really sure why we are using the cached app mechanism though)_
Apart from the hack that you mentioned i.e., parsing an empty folder, another hack could be to use environment variables to skip the DAG parsing for parent process. thoughts?
something like this: https://github.com/verdan/incubator-airflow/pull/6/files

@Fokko could you please take a look?

The error is related to postgres/sqlalchemy and not with the operator. It passed all tests in my travis build:
- [https://travis-ci.org/marcusrehm/incubator-airflow/builds/405467116](https://travis-ci.org/marcusrehm/incubator-airflow/builds/405467116)

@Fokko thank you for your feedback! We tried the approach using Spark too, but some of ours Oracle data bases have security constraints and we can't access it from inside Spark cluster. Actually I don't like CSV too, but we have some use cases where CSV is the best choice because it can be consumed by some legacy systems without bigger efforts and not only by new technologies.

I really appreciated the idea you gave and it made me thought about a version 2 for this operator. Maybe using pyarrow to generate parquet files, so we can choose which format to store.

I did the changes you suggested to the operator.
